<TEXT>
jesse helms the archduke of senate 
conservatives is battling the state department again and his 
private war is gumming up president bushs diplomacy 
this is a tale of three diplomats who want to be ambassadors but 
whose careers have gotten tangled up in a mixture of senate 
politics and personal grudges 
a fourth candidate lost out when his nomination was withdrawn as 
the result of objections from the host country 
helms rnc is angry at the administration over its 
nomination of george fleming jones as ambassador to the tiny south 
american state of guyana 
helms suspects jones of involvement in the 1986 leak of a secret 
chilean military report about the death of an american during a 
violent protest in santiago according to a source who asked not to 
be identified 
helms was infuriated when his own office was blamed for the 
leak he has told the state department that unless it provides 1986 
cables from the us embassy in chile where jones was posted he 
would keep blocking the confirmation the source said 
helms parliamentary maneuvering to block a senate committee 
hearing on jones nomination also wound up delaying confirmation 
hearings for two other ambassadorial nominees g philip hughes 
for barbados and john p leonard for suriname 
while the appointments arent highlevel they illustrate the 
convoluted dealings of the senate and the protracted nature of the 
confirmation process the administration submitted the nominees 
names several months ago and the diplomats may have to wait until 
the new congress convenes next year before their cases are 
resolved 
helms is an old hand at manipulating ambassadorial nominations 
using them as bargaining chips in wheeling and dealing with 
colleagues and the administration the 68yearold standardbearer 
of anticommunism is running for a fourth senate term neckandneck 
against democrat harvey gantt 
one of his betterknown maneuvers was a sixmonth hold on 
the 1987 nomination of april glaspie to become ambassador to iraq 
he took to the senate floor last month to say his objections had 
been vindicated 
glaspie has come in for stinging criticism over her failure to 
tell iraqi president saddam hussein that the united states was 
angry about his threats against kuwait having reported to 
washington that there was no cause for concern she left on 
vacation a day before the aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
sen christopher dodd dconn is upset at helms delay 
tactics according to a congressional source who demanded 
anonymity but hes even more angry at the administration for 
nominating hughes 
hughes served as secretary of the presidents national security 
council during the irancontra affair dodd wants to ask him 
whether he knew that nsc aide oliver north was illegally arranging 
to give the nicaraguan contra rebels money from us arms sales to 
iran 
dodd also objected last year to the nomination of hughes boss 
donald gregg to be ambassador to south korea dodd contended that 
gregg knew of norths doings but gregg eventually was approved 
the fourth nomination frederick vreeland to be ambassador to 
burma is being withdrawn the state department said thursday 
night 
a state department official who asked not to be identified 
said vreelands name is being withdrawn because of objections from 
the military authorities of burma about prodemocracy statements 
vreeland had made during senate testimony 
but vreelands nomination had been in trouble from the start 
sen alfonse damato rny had asked helms to block a vote on 
his confirmation and helms obliged 
damato who isnt a member of the foreign relations committee 
and some committee members were furious at the state department 
for representing vreeland as a foreign service officer at a time 
when he worked undercover for the cia 
vreeland by the way is the son of the late vogue magazine 
editor diana vreeland 
some of vreelands conservative critics also questioned why 
while serving at the us embassy in rome vreeland played down the 
role of soviet and bulgarian intelligence in the 1981 assassination 
attempt of pope john paul ii 
 
editors note ruth sinai covers foreign affairs for the 
associated press 
