<TEXT>
republican senate candidate allen kolstad 
has the white house on his side but sen max baucus has the money 
the lead and widespread appeal among rural montana voters 
kolstad the states lieutenant governor is a wealthy rancher 
and grain farmer who is trying to tar baucus as a liberal in favor 
of big government kolstads conservative pitch even includes a 
reminder that he opposes ted kennedy on most national issues 
but baucus pays close attention to rural and economic concerns 
pet issues include aid to rural hospitals essential air service 
subsidies for rural airline routes and agricultural trade he voted 
against the 1990 farm bill saying it didnt do enough for farmers 
kolstad was at least 20 points behind baucus in an independent 
midseptember poll in addition the republican is up against the 
largest campaign bankroll in montana history 
baucus raised 19 million in the 18 months ending in june a 
princely sum in a state with only 800000 people aggressive 
fundraising efforts continue 
baucus says hes just taking precautions 
kolstad had only 267000 in campaign funds on june 30 but if 
the race gets closer he may look to national gop groups for 
eleventhhour fundraising help 
that approach worked in 1988 when political newcomer conrad 
burns narrowly upset twoterm democratic sen john melcher of 
montana to become the first republican us senator from this state 
in 36 years the huge infusions of cash used to help burns are 
being challenged in a lawsuit and in a complaint before the federal 
election commission 
if someone unfairly attacks me im going to respond says 
baucus i just have be to prepared for the possibility that ill 
face the same deluge of dollars 
in the 1988 race burns a former farmandranch broadcaster 
attacked melcher as a liberal out of touch with conservative rural 
montana 
kolstad has adopted the same strategy 
more federal bureaucracy more federal control the higher 
deficits there are the things im going to be fighting against in 
washington says kolstad 
like burns kolstad was recruited by national gop heavyweights 
including president bush and former president reagan bush raised 
more than 100000 for kolstad when the president traveled to 
montana in july 
kolstad cannot claim the mantle of political outsider he spent 
20 years in the montana legislature before winning the lieutenant 
governorship on the gop ticket with gov stan stephens in 1988 
the stephenskolstad adminstration has not been universally 
popular in montana struggling with tax and budget issues and 
controversial appointees recent polls show his negatives 
nearly doubled since a similar poll in midjune 
kolstad 58 says he is saving his money for a lastminute 
barrage of media advertising attacking baucus on his votes against 
defense spending tax cuts and budgetbalancing measures 
the 48yearold baucus running for a third term has been 
working hard to dispel whatever liberal image he may have had 
he earns relatively high marks from most liberal interest groups 
but insists he doesnt care about ratings 
i dont look left i dont look right i look forward to 
what is the best solution for montana says baucus most people 
are more concerned with producing results for montana than with 
labels 
baucus has barely mentioned kolstad in campaign materials 
preferring instead to emphasize efforts he says have created or 
protected jobs in economically depressed montana 
while differences between the candidates exist baucus is 
prochoice on abortion kolstad is not for example the race has 
generated few fireworks 
</TEXT>
