<TEXT>
the small central african nation of 
rwanda faced a population and ecological crisis even before it was 
invaded this week by armed refugees from neighboring uganda 
an exodus of asian businessmen from their adopted country was an 
ominous sign of deteriorating conditions including overpopulation 
soil erosion and aids 
western experts say more than 50 families of mainly indian and 
pakistani origin have left rwanda in recent months in search of 
fresh opportunities in neighboring tanzania uganda and zaire 
countries also suffering from poverty disease and violence 
reflecting the trend the black market price for us dollars 
preferably in 100 bills favored for smuggling shot up to more 
than double the bank exchange rate of 68 rwanda francs per dollar 
aid agencies estimate that fewer than 500 asian families remain 
in a population of about 8 million people crammed into a rugged 
landscape only the size of maryland 
western experts warn that a human and environmental disaster 
might occur in this decade in the former belgian protectorate 
which gained independence in 1962 
the ecological balance is already threatened 
early this year at least 300 people died in sporadic outbreaks 
of famine in the remote south said a western aid worker 
interviewed by the associated press last month in kigali the 
capital 
in the west lake kivu running most of the way along the border 
with zaire had little fish life left because of caustic runoff 
from cultivated volcanic uplands nearby 
rwanda is africas most densely populated country with an 
average of 566 people living on every rocky and eroded square mile 
of land 
the government of president juvenal habyarimana reports the 
average rwandan woman bears 86 children the highest birth rate in 
the world at the present rate the population will double by the 
year 2006 
land pressure is critical there are simply too many people 
living on too little land said the aid specialist who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
annually cultivated land loses at least 15 inches of topsoil 
to erosion crops are grown on 60degree slopes and in other areas 
the level of acid in exhausted soil is a fraction away from the 
reading that would classify the land as barren 
in 1981 the average rwandans daily nourishment amounted to 
2511 calories it dropped to 1804 calories in 1990 and current 
projections indicate the figure will sink to about 1400 calories 
by the year 2000 
the united nations food and agriculture organization says that 
adults need a basic minimum of 2100 calories a day to lead a 
healthy life 
in 10 years experts predict hunger will be widespread and food 
aid will be needed on a scale not seen since the ethiopian famine 
of the mid1980s 
even if all the remaining patches of nature preserve and forest 
were turned over to agriculture additional food production would 
only cover the population growth for two years a kigalibased 
european researcher told the ap 
without the forests acting as waterretaining sponges the 
ultimate ecological collapse would hasten said the researcher 
speaking on condition of anonymity 
in rwandas towns where only 5 percent of the population live 
up to 40 percent of the people are estimated to be infected by the 
virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome a mainly 
heterosexual disease in africa 
a large proportion of these may die within the next decade say 
hospital officials also 1 in every 5 babies born in the towns can 
be expected to die before age 4 having contracted the aids virus 
in an infected mothers womb 
</TEXT>
