rep dana rohrabacher says hell fight a new 
compromise bill on the national endowment for the arts as a piece 
of flimflummery that will do nothing to halt federal support 
for obscene and sacrilegious art 
the california republican a staunch conservative and ardent foe 
of the federal arts agency said he will seek to defeat the 
bipartisan measure drafted by reps pat williams dmont and e 
thomas coleman rmo the house begins debate on the proposal next 
week 
its a sham and a facade to deceive the voters rohrabacher 
said its a total fraud it portends to offer some kind of 
restrictions on federal funding for obscenity when in reality it 
opens the floodgates 
williams and coleman who announced agreement on their 
compromise thursday after weeks of intensive negotiations proposed 
to extend the neas life for three years and let the courts decide 
whether federally subsidized arts projects are obscene 
rohrabacher said their bill was the type of flimflummery that 
makes americans cynical about the politicians in washington 
he said it reflects the democratic leaderships loyalty to a 
fringe of freak artists who insist they have the right to federal 
tax dollars to produce pornography and sacrilegious art 
rohrabacher says he will introduce a floor amendment that would 
prohibit nea support for a laundry list of taboos including 
obscenity indecency child pornography and works that attack 
religion desecrate the american flag or contain any part of a 
human fetus 
coleman and rep paul henry rmich hinted that the real aim 
of rohrabacher and his conservative allies was to dismantle the nea 
or abolish it entirely 
the question is whether to dismantle this agency or make it 
better henry said this bill would make it better 
williams predicted that their measure will pass the house by a 
significant majority of both democrats and republicans 
the bill could provide house members a way to defuse the 
politically explosive issue of federal support for obscene art 
in an election year 
the controversy began 18 months ago when conservative lawmakers 
and religious fundamentalists attacked the nea for subsidizing 
exhibitions of works by photographer robert mapplethorpe and artist 
andres serrano which they denounced as obscene and blasphemous 
the williamscoleman compromise would forbid the endowment from 
financing obscenity but it would shift from the nea to the courts 
the burden of deciding what is obscene based on the supreme 
courts 1973 guidelines 
under the bill any grant recipient who is convicted of 
violating obscenity laws would be required to repay the government 
and would be barred from receiving further nea grants for at least 
three years 
in a bow to republican demands the bill also would boost the 
states share of nea grant money from 20 percent to 35 percent over 
the next three years coleman originally had sought to shift 60 
percent of nea funds to the control of state arts agencies 
the measure also would make sweeping changes in the endowments 
grantmaking procedures with the aim of making the nea more 
accountable to the taxpaying public it would bolster the nea 
chairmans authority to make final grant decisions and dilute the 
panels of outside artists and arts managers which select grant 
applications for approval 
similar legislation is awaiting senate floor action also headed 
for the house floor is a separate bill to provide 180 million in 
nea spending next year a 5 percent increase over its current 171 
million budget 
meanwhile nea chairman john e frohnmayer and evangelist pat 
robertson clashed again thursday over robertsons claim that 
federal funds supported an atlanta puppet show featuring simulated 
oral sex 
in a sept 28 letter to robertson released thursday frohnmayer 
vigorously denied that any nea funds were spent on the puppet show 
or its sponsor the arts festival of atlanta 
robertson ignored frohnmayers demand for a public retraction of 
his categorically false allegation the evangelist told his 
television audience that if members of congress vote to give the 
nea more money next year it shows they are totally out of touch 
with america and with morality 
