<TEXT>
an agriculture department survey shows the 
loss of wetlands on private lands nationwide slowed significantly 
during the mid1980s 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said thursday that the new 
figures by the departments soil conservation service or scs 
indicated wetland losses ranged between 100000 and 200000 acres 
per year from 1982 to 1987 including areas that reverted to open 
water 
this was significantly less than wetland loss estimates 
before 198287 he said 
no previous scs estimates were available spokeswoman diana 
morse said the agency began its fiveyear surveys in 1977 the new 
figures comparing 1987 with 1982 were the first she said 
estimates used in the surveys were based on information 
collected on 300000 sample sites across the nation 
the latest figures came from the agencys 1987 national 
resources inventory or nri which is conducted on nonfederal 
lands every five years in cooperation with the iowa state 
university statistical laboratory 
officials said the inventory serves as the principal source of 
information on the status condition and trends of soil water and 
related resources it also provides a soilandwater data base for 
nonfederal rural lands 
the report said there were about 82 million ares of wetlands on 
nonfederal rural lands in 1987 down from 832 million acres in 
1982 
however scs estimated the loss of wetlands to agricultural and 
development uses at closer to 500000 acres or an average of 
100000 acres per year 
the remaining change in wetlands was due to factors such as 
300000 acres changing from private to federal ownership still 
likely remaining in wetlands but not included in the scs 
nonfederal lands inventory and over 400000 acres that changed 
to open water primarily adjacent to the great salt lake in utah 
and in southern louisiana the report said 
of the nearly 500000 acres lost to agriculture and development 
about 215000 were converted farmland including wetlands drying up 
because of drought and about 280000 acres to development 
regionally the nri indicated wetland losses over the fiveyear 
period were greatest in the southeast mississippi delta states 
and the great lakes states 
losses were reported at 170000 acres in the southeast 150000 
in the delta and 80000 in the great lakes 
morse said there were no available breakdowns by state and that 
the scs considered those estimates too inexact for publishing she 
said the regional estimates were the only ones available 
 
washington ap farm cooperatives hurting badly a few years 
ago from the financial crunch on producers have recovered most of 
their old zing an annual report by the agriculture department 
shows 
in 1989 the report said coops reported their secondhighest 
net income and thirdhighest sales 
overall combined business volume was shown at 704 billion up 
6 percent from 664 billion in 1988 that was topped only by the 
record 73 billion in 1984 and the 715 billion in 1981 
net incomes in 1989 totaled nearly 19 billion the report 
said that was up 123 percent from 1988 the record was 194 
billion in 1980 
randall e torgerson administrator of the departments 
agricultural cooperative service said the higher business volume 
was due mostly to larger output of grains and oilseeds higher 
price for poultry and higher prices and sales of fruits and 
vegetables fertilizers and farm chemicals 
production of feed grains and soybeans was up sharply last year 
from 1988 when drought reduced yields 
increased earnings of farm supply coops were a major 
contributing factor to the nearrecord income despite a increase 
in the number of cooperatives reporting losses in 1989 the report 
said those increased to 574 from 364 in 1988 however the amount 
of losses decreased to 824 million last year from 1647 million 
the previous year 
total cooperative business volume includes the value of products 
marketed the sale of farm supplies such as fertilizer chemicals 
fuel and feed to members and other customers and receipts from 
services including trucking storage ginning and artificial 
insemination 
torgerson said the number of farm cooperatives and members 
continued a longtime downward trend 
coop units declined to 4799 last year from 4937 in 1988 he 
said memberships dropped 14 percent to 414 million the number 
of memberships exceeds the number of farms because many farmers 
belong to more than one coop 
 
washington ap an agriculture department scientist says that 
after 10 years he is close to developing a soybean that has both 
high protein and high yields 
plant geneticist joseph w burton of the departments 
agricultural research service said in a report that preliminary 
results show a boost in protein content to almost 47 percent from 
about 42 percent 
the preliminary results also show excellent yields for the new 
bean he said overall it could mean a possible boost in revenue 
to soybean producers of 1 to 150 per bushel 
burton who works at the agencys soybean and nitrogen fixation 
research unit in raleigh nc said it will take another year of 
testing to determine how best to make commercial use of the new 
bean 
