state officials sued the national 
republican senatorial campaign committee charging that a gop 
fundraising letter is deceptive and may defraud the public 
the suit filed thursday by attorney general robert j del tufo 
and director of consumer affairs patricia royer asks for a court 
hearing on the committees mailing of 25 checks to residents if a 
person endorses the check and provides a bank account number the 
republican committee is authorized to automatically withdraw 1250 
a month from that persons bank account 
in 20 years of experience with consumer fraud i have never 
before seen this type of fraudulent action said ms royer i 
am very concerned that every con artist out there will use 
automatic funds transfer as a way to defraud the public let this 
quick action serve as a warning that this behavior will not be 
tolerated in new jersey the suit was filed in state superior 
court in essex county it seeks fines costs and restitution of any 
money collected 
ms royer said the terms of the agreement that would allow the 
republican committee to withdraw 1250 a month from residents 
bank accounts are printed on the reverse side of the check 
but the print is so small a person with 2020 vision would 
have a problem reading it without the aid of a magnifier she 
said 
national republican senatorial campaign committee spokeswoman 
wendy burnley sharply denied that the fundraising letter was 
improper suggesting that complaints against it may be politically 
motivated ms burnley acknowledged that the letter has prompted 
complaints in at least six states in addition to new jersey 
