<TEXT>
white house aide ronald kaufman and 
another republican lost their bids to be dropped from a lawsuit 
charging the springfield police union conspired to disrupt the 
democratic state convention last june 
in a ruling issued thursday in hampden county superior court 
judge william w simons refused to dismiss claims by the state 
democratic committee in its suit against kaufman and stephen 
deangelis a onetime campaign operative for joseph malone a gop 
candidate for state treasurer 
the suit charges that kaufman and deangelis worked with the 
police union in its picketing of the convention which delayed the 
proceedings for four hours and was politically embarrassing for the 
democrats 
simons also ruled that police pickets at the convention had 
verbally and physically assaulted some persons outside the 
convention hall 
simons said the democrats including five convention delegates 
had presented enough facts to support their claims against kaufman 
the unionnews of springfield reported 
the judge also said there is enough of a factual dispute 
over deangelis involvement in the convention disruption to allow 
the case against him to continue 
the judge said the democrats state facts which support their 
allegations about kaufman and allege with specificity that 
kaufman met with planned and assisted the picketing by the police 
union 
kaufman is a deputy assistant to president george bush 
the police union and its president patrolman robert jacobson 
also are defendants in the suit 
the suit includes allegations that the police union violated 
delegates civil rights by keeping them from the convention june 2 
