<TEXT>
the latest photographs from the crippled hubble 
space telescope have lifted much of the gloom that descended on 
scientists after a focusing flaw was discovered last summer 
at the same time astronomers acknowledge that one of the 15 
billion space observatorys prime missions peering out into the 
farthest reaches of space can not be undertaken until the flaw is 
corrected 
when the space telescope was put into orbit 381 miles above the 
earth by the space shuttle on april 25 scientists were excited by 
the prospect of measuring the speed with which the outermost edges 
of the universe are expanding now that work will have to postponed 
three or four years 
first of all the problem with the optics are there and they 
will have to be fixed that is certainly true said riccardo 
giacconi director of the space telescope science institute 
however the other thing that emerged as a result of the 
photographs is that some of the basic capacity has been 
preserved 
we can use that optical power but only for sources that are 
not too far away that are bright enough 
in practice that means astronomers will have to reorder their 
priorities and the institute is currently reevaluating 160 
research projects originally planned for the hubble giacconi said 
with computer enhancement studies of relatively nearby objects 
and phenomena including novas will be possible with the same 
degree of accuracy as originally envisioned he said 
one photo presented thursday by the science institute offered 
the clearest view yet of enigmatic pluto the ninth and only planet 
that hasnt been visited by a flyby spacecraft and its moon 
charon there also was a shot of startling clarity of saturn 
scientists said that some photographs from hubble had 10 times 
the resolution that would have been possible from earthbound 
telescopes 
the mood at the institute thursday was much improved from last 
summer when it was discovered that a mirror on the telescope had 
manufacturing problems the observatorys initial pictures were 
blurred and of severely limited value to astronomers 
scientists are currently weighing how best to repair flaws in 
the telescopes mirrors a replacement widefield camera is now 
being built at the jet propulsion laboratory in california and 
plans call for it to be delivered to hubble on a space shuttle 
flight in 1993 
engineers plan to install correcting optics in the replacement 
camera to compensate for the flawed mirrors 
within the next few weeks the hubbles spectrographic 
instruments are expected to begin transmitting data back to earth 
on temperature motion and composition of stars results from these 
studies are usually expressed in numbers and graphs not pictures 
