<TEXT>
officials in central and south florida are 
advising people to avoid going outdoors at nightfall because of the 
increasing risk of bites from mosquitoes spreading encephalitis 
the number of cases of st louis encephalitis has reached 28 
since the first was reported in august fifteen people were 
hospitalized with the disease which causes brain swelling two are 
comatose another seven cases are suspected and await further 
tests 
the disease kills about 7 percent of its victims little can be 
done to treat it but it can be avoided health officials are 
telling everyone to stay indoors after dark and if they do go 
outside to wear protective clothing and insect repellent 
the outbreak is floridas most threatening in 13 years in 1977 
eight people died in the last statewide outbreak of the st louis 
strain of encephalitis which causes flulike symptoms 
some communities are spraying with insecticide others are 
ordering school activities to cease by dark 
in broward county school principals have been ordered to cancel 
nature hikes camping trips fishing trips and waterrelated 
activities that would increase student exposure to mosquitoes 
broward schools didnt cancel evening school activities but 
instead will have their ball fields sprayed with insecticide before 
night games a similar tactic is being used in sumter county 
in martin county beaches and county parks were ordered closed 
at night 
