<DOCNO> AP901005-0075 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many of the inmates on oregons death row are 
headed back to new sentencing hearings in the states already 
sluggish court system because of a us supreme court ruling 
its not going to shut the system down but anything with a 
death penalty attached to it takes more time and effort than those 
cases without the death penalty said phil lemman an assistant 
to state attorney general dave frohnmayer 
the us supreme court agreed monday with the oregon supreme 
court that three death sentences should be overturned 
the state court had said that because of a 1989 us supreme 
court decision the defendants were entitled to have mitigating 
evidence presented to the sentencing jury 
the result is that many of the 23 men sentenced to death before 
the 1989 decision may qualify for new sentencing hearings 
oregons capital punishment law passed by voters in 1984 
establishes a twostep court proceeding 
the jury first decides whether a defendant is guilty of 
aggravated murder if guilty the jury decides whether the 
defendant should die by injection 
under the initial version of the law a death sentence was 
imposed if the jury unanimously found the defendant posed a future 
threat of violence acted deliberately in the killing and killed 
without provocation 
the 1989 legislature revised the law to take into account the 
us supreme court ruling the oregon supreme court then fashioned 
an additional question on mitigating circumstances for jurors to 
consider 
the court said the jury can weigh any aspect of a defendants 
background or any circumstances of the offense that would justify 
life imprisonment instead 
frohnmayer appealed the state supreme court ruling arguing that 
it went far beyond constitutional requirements he said mitigating 
factors for the jury to consider should be limited to those bearing 
on a defendants moral blameworthiness 
lemman said it will be some time before its determined how many 
new sentencing proceedings will be needed 
in any case he said the sessions will require time and 
expense 
these are not going to be quick twohour hearings he said 
the law allows evidence from the trial to submitted to the 
sentencing jury and witnesses can be recalled to testify new 
lawyers also could be involved 
the chief criminal judge in multnomah county which has the 
states biggest trial court system said new death sentence 
proceedings will add to the work but probably wont disrupt court 
dockets 
circuit judge philip abraham said it appears up to six 
deathsentence cases will require new hearings in his county 
it will impact the system somewhat but i dont see it as 
insurmountable abraham said 
his court system handles about 5000 felony cases annually and 
had 31 murder cases pending at the beginning of october 
the oregon supreme court already had sent eight death penalty 
cases back to trial courts for new sentencing hearings at the time 
of the us supreme court decision 
prosecutors have the option of seeking life terms instead of 
death sentences and one district attorney so far has case has 
decided on a life sentence 
in three other cases death sentences were set aside when murder 
convictions were reversed by the state supreme court 
all death sentence cases automatically are appealed to the state 
supreme court 
</TEXT>
