<TEXT>
the education department friday said harvard 
university has been cleared of charges its undergraduate admission 
policies discriminate against asianamerican applicants 
michael williams assistant secretary for civil rights said an 
examination of records found asian americans were admitted to 
harvard at a lower rate than white applicants mainly because of the 
preference given to children of alumni and recruited athletes 
groups in which there are few asian americans 
while these preferences have an adverse effect on asian 
americans we determined that they were longstanding and 
legitimate and not a pretext for discrimination said williams 
who made completing reviews at harvard and ucla his highest 
priority when he joined the agency in july 
on monday the department announced a finding of discrimination 
against asian americans seeking admission to the university of 
california at los angeles graduate mathematics program ucla now 
must offer admission to five asianamerican students who had been 
discriminatorily denied admission 
williams said the office of civil rights could find no evidence 
of a quota at harvard limiting asian americans who have gone from 
being 55 percent of the class in 1983 to being 196 percent of the 
class of 1994 
the twoyear investigation included a review of thousands of 
applicant files and 10 years of applicant data provided by harvard 
as well as dozens of interviews with staff and other individuals 
williams said 
investigatios have been conducted in response to complaints 
alleging that several schools including harvard and ucla were in 
violation of title vi of the 1964 civil rights act the law 
stipulates that recipients of federal funds cannot discriminate on 
the basis of race color or national origin 
</TEXT>
