<TEXT>
the mormon churchs 160th semiannual 
general conference this weekend finds the faith a study in familiar 
contrasts a robust and growing membership headed by an aged 
prophet in declining health 
the faiths tradition of succession by apostolic seniority has 
bred a gerontocracy that averages 708 years of age and produces 
presidents considerably older and more prone to infirmity 
i dont think anyone has to be told of the negatives of a 
gerontocracy in terms of the medical realities said d michael 
quinn a former brigham young university professor whos writing a 
history of the churchs hierarchy 
the other problem is that you have at the highest leadership 
of the church men who are at least two generations 
sometimes three generations removed from the majority of the 
population of the church 
but there are also advantages in having wellseasoned 
administrators in the governing first presidency and its advisory 
body the council of the twelve apostles he said 
the 160yearold church is struggling to cope with a rate of 
growth that has seen membership more than double every 15 years 
since 1945 
at that rate the church of jesus christ of latterday saints 
with 75 million members and more than 40000 fulltime 
missionaries will have 265 million members by 2080 according to a 
study by rodney stark a nonmormon professor of sociology and 
comparative religion at the university of washington the church 
has 42 million members in the united states 
what you have to realize is that a group can look small for a 
long time and then all of a sudden it just explodes stark said 
so just wait until all these people convert their relatives and 
see how it really kicks in 
the latest casualty of advancing years is ezra taft benson the 
churchs president since 1985 mormons believe jesus christ directs 
the churchs affairs through the president who is considered a 
prophet seer and revelator 
benson 91 remained hospitalized friday in serious condition 
two weeks after surgery for blood clots on the brain 
he was able to maintain a full schedule for only the first 
couple of years of his fiveyear tenure his predecessor spencer 
w kimball was mostly incapacitated for the five years before his 
death in 1985 at age 90 
but church spokesman don lefevre said the hierarchy doesnt miss 
a beat when its leader falters 
when the president of the church becomes incapacitated the 
network is already in place and his counselors and the council of 
the twelve apostles simply carry on lefevre said 
when a church president dies the office is filled by the 
president of the twelve that bodys most senior apostle howard w 
hunter a former corporate lawyer is bensons heir apparent 
hunter will be 83 nov 14 a widower he remarried last spring 
and puts in full days lefevre said 
church leaders in 1978 provided for retirement of members of the 
first quorum of the seventy which acts under the direction of the 
twelve giving some members emeritus status 
the move was seen as a way to inject new blood in the hierarchy 
but the policy has never been extended to include the twelve 
but eventually quinn said the mormon gerontocracy likely will 
face a crisis of succession where the heir to the prophetic mantle 
is himself unable not simply to walk unable to talk but unable 
to function in any recognizable way in front of an audience to even 
acknowledge he is the president of the church 
theyve been spared that thus far but if that occurs i dont 
know what theyll do he said 
