<TEXT>
americas unemployment rate worsened for the 
third straight month in september the government said friday many 
analysts saw the report as evidence that the economy has quietly 
slipped into a recession 
the increase in the civilian jobless rate to 57 percent 
coupled with unemployment rises in july and august marked the 
first time since the depths of the 198182 recession that the 
jobless rate has increased three months in a row the government 
said 
lets face it its a trend weve been pushed over the edge 
were in a recession and its going to go on for at least six 
to nine months said david wyss an analyst for drimcgraw hill 
the bush administration insists the economy has not fallen into 
a recession but presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said after 
fridays announcement that were certainly concerned about the 
economy 
fitzwater said that concern was heightened by the house 
rejection of a proposed deficitreduction agreement which the 
administration had touted as the budgetary fix needed to convince 
the federal reserve board to lower interest rates and spur the 
flagging economy 
today we see unemployment jump to 57 percent which only 
emphasizes the urgency of this situation fitzwater said 
but many analysts said fridays report showing unemployment up 
01 percentage point and at its highest level since the spring of 
1988 made clear that the economy has lost the strength necessary 
to avoid toppling over the edge into a recession 
fallen off were in midair and i dont think weve reached 
the bottom yet said ian borsook a senior economist with merrill 
lynch 
more industries lost jobs than gained them in september causing 
an overall loss of 101000 jobs from nonfarm payrolls the labor 
departmet said 
about 42000 of those losses were census workers laid off by the 
government but janet norwood the commissioner labor statistics 
noted that the weakness in the september job market had hit 
factories and service industries as well 
few areas of the economy are escaping the downward tug of the 
current economic slowdown mrs norwood said 
the nations employment picture began a downward spiral in july 
as the economy failed to produce enough jobs to keep up with the 
number of americans looking for work since then the jobless rate 
has risen 05 percentage point from junes 52 percent 
the rapid jump in unemployment reflects an economy that was 
showing little signs of life even before iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait sent oil prices soaring and increased fears of an imminent 
downturn 
the governments technical definition of a recession two 
quarters of economic decline as measured by the gross national 
product has not officially been met 
indeed the gnp for the years third quarter is expected to post 
a small gain even with septembers lackluster performance many 
analysts think a fullfledged downturn will take hold in the fourth 
quarter 
the 101000job loss in september though inflated by the census 
workers was the biggest job decline since the economy lost 104000 
jobs in june 1986 the government said a year ago the economy was 
creating nearly 200000 jobs a month 
the slump in the manufacturing sector continued in september 
with factory jobs posting a 66000job loss there have been more 
than 500000 jobs lost in that sector since january 1989 
construction also continued its slide in september posting the 
fourth decline in as many months as the weakness in the housing 
market showed no signs of abating jobs in that sector have fallen 
by more than 100000 in recent months 
the serviceproducing sector which until a few months ago had 
been enjoying robust job growth actually lost 17000 jobs in 
september 
within the sector the services industry itself which employs 
one in four nonfarm workers added only 20000 jobs one of the 
smallest gains since the 198182 recession mrs norwood said 
labor costs which are frequently blamed for worsening inflation 
problems rose a sharp 05 percent the average hourly worker made 
1013 an hour in september up from 973 in september 1989 
in a separate calculation of unemployment that counts members of 
the armed services stationed in the united states the september 
jobless rate was 56 percent up from 55 percent in august 
