prepared for the worst an energy 
department team equipped with millions of dollars worth of 
radiation monitors staked out kennedy space center for saturdays 
launch of a shuttle with a plutonium cargo 
it would be irresponsible not to be ready in the event of an 
accident said energy department spokesman dave jackson 
there is 237 pounds of plutonium in the space shuttle 
jackson said friday even if there is an accident and no release 
we have to document the fact that there is no release and make 
people understand there is no hazard 
about twothirds of the 70member team were to be standing by 
with portable radiation monitors during the fueling of discovery 
late friday and early saturday and during liftoff scheduled for 
saturday morning 
energy department officials also planned to have a plane 
circling overhead at launch time to measure radiation in the air in 
the event of a challengerlike accident 
the danger will linger for 7 hours after liftoff when the 
