<TEXT>
the guinness book of records first published to 
settle pub disputes and other friendly debates issued its 1991 
edition friday with 3000 new records revealing the lengths people 
will go to get their names in print 
englishman dale lyons ran 299 miles in four hours and 18 
minutes balancing a fresh egg in a dessert spoon in cracking the 
previous egg and spoon race record lyons gained a place in the 
book 
the royal army ordinance corps broke the round the world driving 
record between may 13 and june 22 traveling 251878 miles in 39 
days 23 hours and 35 minutes 
there is a fascination with breaking a record people like to 
feel they can actually get their name in a book said cathy 
brooks the spokeswoman for guinness publishing 
the latest edition shows that americans continue to pin their 
shot at the big time on big food 
students and staff at lawrence university in appleton wis 
