<TEXT>
the yanomami indians the largest 
known primitive tribe in existence may be changing from a nomadic 
to a stable community two leading scientists said friday 
some groups in the tribe which inhabits the tropical amazon 
rain forest along venezuelas border with brazil are also 
experiencing a population growth equal to about 2 percent a year 
they said 
charles brewercarias a venezuelan naturalist said the 
population growth coupled with a change in cultivation habits were 
basic conditions for transition to a stable community 
brewercarias and napoleon a chagnon an anthropology professor 
at the university of california at santa barbara led a 40day 
expedition that in recent weeks contacted four yanomami groups 
about 14000 yanomamis inhabit the venezuelan amazon and 9000 
live across the border in the brazilian rainforest scientists say 
it is believed the yanomamis migrated from the caribbean region 
thousands of years ago because they burn their dead and drink a 
solution of the ashes evidence of them is hard to trace 
the yanomamis hunt with poisoned arrows and many use primitive 
tools they shun clothes decorate their bodies with fruit dye and 
flowers and live under huge palm huts in small communities 
the yanomami are the largest tribe with little or no contact 
with the modern world 
the yanomami groups are based on parental ties but once they 
reach a number of 200 to 250 parental relationship weakens among 
yanomami and they apparently split forming a new group that settles 
elsewhere scientists say 
chagnon who has studied the yanomami indians for 25 years said 
his conclusions on population growth among the venezuelan groups 
come from studies on the reproduction of yanomami women from 
different villages 
on the brazilian side of the border the yanomamis havent been 
as lucky suffering at the hands of gold prospectors who have 
brought disease and chemicals to the primitive communities 
speaking from california chagnon said he also has collected 
data on settlement and migration he said most existing yanomami 
villages emerged from a single village between 120 and 150 years 
ago and then scattered 
the original village had a population of no more than 300 their 
descendents dispersed over 12 villages and now number over 2000 
they increased more than sixfold during the past 120150 
years by demographic standards that is a very high rate of 
expansion it would be a high rate even if it were half of this 
he said 
chagnon and brewercarias are codirecting a project to study 
the yanomami and other indian cultures over the next 10 years 
the recent expedition which covered the high siapa river basin 
near the brazilian border was supported by the university of 
california and fundafaci a private venezuelan foundation 
brewercarias said the expedition found evidence that new 
splinter groups were spreading over the brazilianvenezuelan 
border some have shifted cultivations from banana to manioc 
it seems they are experimenting with new staples 
brewercarias said 
it took nine hours of helicopter flight before the expedition 
found and contacted the first yanomami group still untouched and 
up to that moment totally isolated from our culture 
brewercarias said 
in brazil the yanomamis have been pushed deep into the jungle by 
gold prospectors who have invaded their lands seeking gold and 
diamonds about 3000 have died over the past three years most 
from exposure to disease 
because of their isolation the indians have no immunity against 
common viruses and can easily die from flu or cold 
</TEXT>
