president bush on friday proposed legislation 
to give a decade of preferable trade benefits to peru colombia 
ecuador and bolivia in thanks for their cooperation in the war 
against drugs 
the andean trade preference act is patterned after the caribbean 
basin initiative that gives special trade benefits to caribbean 
nations 
the andean proposal bush sent to congress also addresses the 
long festering trade dispute with colombia over cut flowers by 
making them duty free 
it would authorize duty free treatment for 10 years for some 
imports from the countries along the andean mountains which also 
are the principle source and production countries for the cocaine 
trade 
products particularly sensitive to import competition will 
not be duty free the white house said those products include 
textiles and apparel canned tuna petroleum products watches and 
watch parts luggage leather apparel and flat goods will still be 
dutiable but under a duty reduction program 
the administration is trying to provide economic incentives and 
assistance to south american countries that have suffered in 
cracking down on lucrative drug industries that greatly buttress 
their poor economies 
the idea behind this legislation is to give the countries an 
extra boost by providing a special 10year access to the 
american market bush said as he signed the transmittal to 
congress 
the trade measure is a follow up to the drug summit meeting bush 
held with the presidents of peru bolivia and colombia in 
cartagena colombia he promised to work on expanding economic 
opportunities for countries that cooperate with us efforts to 
interdict drugs and halt production of illicit narcotics 
enactment of the measure bush said in a letter to congress 
will permit the united states to support the efforts of the 
andean countries to eliminate the production processing and 
