beginning until today and we feel that possibly the worst part of 
the epidemic may still be ahead said jonathan day an 
entomologist with the university of floridas institute of food and 
agricultural sciences 
the season for transmission of the virus typically runs until 
middecember as mosquitoes continue to breed and bite the disease 
can be expected to spread with them day said 
if we get a cold snap it will kill them its all up to mother 
nature durfee said 
very few mosquitoes actually are carriers said durfee 
he said the disease is cyclical occurring every 10 to 15 years 
because of a combination of factors such as rainfall and mosquito 
hatchings 
the st louis strain last surfaced in florida 13 years ago with 
110 cases confirmed and eight deaths attributed to it 
