<TEXT>
two years after dozens of hispanics were rounded 
up at a racetrack lawyers say they have won a major victory over 
government officials who tried to deport the people without proving 
they were illegal aliens 
the case was widely viewed as a test of alien rights the 
defendants refused to answer questions about how and when they 
entered the country citing fifth amendment rights against 
selfincrimination 
the immigration and naturalization service argued that this 
silence on its own demonstrated that the defendants were illegal 
aliens last year an immigration judge agreed 
but three weeks ago the federal board of immigration appeals 
reversed that ruling ending the deportation proceedings against 
one of the defendants 
the appeals board said the ins approach would shift the burden 
of proof at a deportation proceeding 
since the decision people have come forward to say federal 
immigration officials used similar tactics in other cases said dan 
kanstroom a boston college law professor who assisted in the 
appeal 
but he said the boston case marked the first national test of 
this strategy 
its very important that it stopped here he said 
daniel levy staff attorney at the national immigration law 
center in los angeles said if the governments arguments had been 
upheld it would have significantly broadened ins powers 
they would have been able to stop anybody on the street send 
them to court and if the person remains quiet the person could be 
deported levy said in a telephone interview 
verne jervis spokesman for the ins said friday that agency 
officials were still reviewing the boards decision and had not 
decided what action to take 
during the dawn raid oct 21 1988 at suffolk downs 
authorities seized 83 salvadoran mexican brazilian and cuban 
stable hands 
of those people six were found to be in the united states 
lawfully some of the remainder returned to their homelands while 
others admitted their illegal status and applied for asylum 
by the time the appeals board issued its decision 30 defendants 
remained 
on friday lawyers who teamed up to fight the ins gathered to 
plot their next moves the appeals board decision specifically 
discussed the case of only one defendant but kanstroom said it 
would apply to the others 
the clients can choose to have their deportation proceedings 
terminated or may eventually decide to return home or can take 
other steps such as seeking political asylum he said 
judith gail dein one of the lawyers who filed the appeal said 
no matter what the clients decide the appeals board has sent a 
strong message against the violation of peoples basic rights 
it feels real good that somebody put a stop to that she 
said 
