<DOCNO> AP901005-0118 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the decline of american banks compared with 
their foreign competitors threatens to harm an already weak us 
economy and diminish the nations world influence a congressional 
report concludes 
a house banking committee task force chaired by rep john j 
lafalce dny strongly suggested that the depressionera 
constraints barring banks from expanding into new services such as 
securities underwriting and insurance must fall if us banks are 
to regain their edge 
there appears to be little doubt that repeal of the securities 
restrictions imposed on us banks would enhance the 
competitiveness of us banks globally it said 
the panel also criticized remaining barriers preventing banks 
from expanding across state lines and compares the convoluted us 
regulatory system with its more streamlined counterparts overseas 
the 488page report which was conceived as a factfinding study 
rather than a vehicle for legislative recommendations has not been 
issued yet a draft circulated to the 20 task force members was 
obtained by the associated press it stresses the importance of a 
competitive banking system to the economy 
we must have a successful productive economy if we are to 
address societal needs and solve societal problems and a 
successful financial services delivery system is at the crux of a 
successful and productive economic machine the task force said 
the panel was formed last november and held a series of hearings 
through august with appearances from all of the major us 
financial regulators as well as private us and foreign business 
executives 
its research is intended by lafalce a strong advocate of 
expanding bank powers to serve as the basis for debate next year 
when the bush administration intends to submit its plan for the 
most significant overhaul of the us financial system in 50 years 
dramatic changes in financial services technology have 
increasingly shifted business away from banks toward other firms 
particularly brokerage houses the report said 
it is clear that the relative competitive position of us 
banks has deteriorated significantly as the us banking system has 
remained static in a changing world it said 
yet the us continues to develop policy for its financial 
services industry in a myopic and indeed isolationist way it 
said 
as europe prepares for economic union in 1992 its banks are 
increasingly adopting the universal banking model combining 
traditional commercial banking with securities underwriting and 
insurance the task force said 
the japanese financial structure is more split on paper but 
unofficial cooperative relationships among firms known as the 
keiretsu system allow japanese banks to provide a wider array 
of services than us banks it said 
thus it will become more difficult for us banks functioning 
under a decadesold system to compete at home and abroad it said 
increasingly us banks will be competing at home and abroad 
against foreign financial institutions that can offer customers a 
full array of financial services products us banks are not 
capable of providing it said 
foreign banks particularly japanese banks are making 
increasing inroads in the united states the report noted in 
california for instance japanese banks control about onequarter 
of all banking assets 
because of laws restricting the geographic expansion of us 
banks often it is easier for a foreign bank to acquire a us 
institution it said 
increasing foreign ownership of us banks raises important 
questions about americans ability to manage their own economy it 
said if foreign control of us financial institutions had been 
greater after the 1987 stock market crash the situation could 
have proved more difficult for the federal reserve to control 
the report said 
when credit is scarce us companies could find themselves at 
the tail end of a very long queue behind borrowers from britain 
japan west germany and other countries it said 
also a diminished us banking industry leaves us 
policymakers in the awkward position of being unable to help 
procure finance for the economic policies they encourage foreign 
governments to take 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

