<TEXT>
advocates for the blind the obese and 
hispanics on friday questioned a federal regulation that says 
people with disabilities and no understanding of english cannot sit 
next to exit doors on us airlines 
the federal aviation administration regulation says only people 
who are able and willing to open exit doors in emergencies and 
understand flight crews and assist them with evacuations may be 
seated next to the doors the regulation took effect friday 
people barred from such seats include parents with small 
children people considered too frail to operate the door 
passengers with broken limbs and other disabilities the obese 
children under 15 and the blind 
some airlines already prohibit blind travelers from sitting in 
exitdoor seats and several sightless people have been arrested in 
recent years for refusing to move from seats 
marc maurer president of the national federation of the blind 
said the rule is discriminatory and called it an example of the 
fear that people have of being blind 
a blind person is accustomed to dealing with working without 
lights he said they dont have a single piece of evidence 
that shows that blind people are hazardous yet they make this 
judgement 
others said they were concerned with how the faa would determine 
obesity or the ability to read and understand english 
i understand the faas concern but i feel theyre making 
certainly an arbitrary judgment about the mobility of fat 
people said sally e smith executive director of the national 
association to advance fat acceptance 
were very concerned about the potential disparate effect of 
the proposed regulation on hispanics and others said charles 
kamasaki vice president for research advocacy and legislation for 
the national council of la raza a hispanic organization 
are they going to give iq tests what constitutes limited 
english proficiency even if the regulation were justified were 
concerned about its application in practice he said 
paul steucke a spokesman for the faa said airlines were 
directed to come up with their own guidelines to determine who is 
qualified to sit next to the exits 
theres discretion involved he said you might have 
somebody whos 250 pounds if theyre 6foot4 there probably wont 
be a problem if theyre 4foot1 there might be 
william e oriol a spokesman for the national council on the 
aging aid the organization was still examining the regulation 
reaction from passengers who traveled through three us 
airports on friday was mixed 
some said they were concerned about the englishonly provision 
they already have everything written in english and spanish 
anyway maybe they should have bilingual people sitting there 
said jennette heck who flew in to miami from new orleans but i 
dont think handicapped people should sit right by the door they 
could get hurt in the panic 
martin cohen 48 of easton pa favored the rule 
i have a young child and when im traveling with her they 
dont want us to sit next to the emergency door said cohen who 
was at bostons logan international airport the idea is to get 
the exit open in a plane crash you should have someone who could 
open the exit 
jeff bank 27 of new york who also was in boston said you 
have to do whats necessary to protect all the passengers and it 
just makes sense 
