<DOCNO> AP901005-0124 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a traveling exhibit of robert mapplethorpes 
photographs closed friday leaving in its wake protests and a 
conservative attack on the national endowment for the arts 
at an earlier stop in cincinnati the exhibit prompted an 
obscenity prosecution of an art gallery and its director a case 
that ended friday in acquittal the jury in the nations first such 
prosecution of an art gallery rejected prosecutors argument that 
seven of the pictures were obscene 
cincinnatis contemporary art gallery and its director dennis 
barrie were acquitted of charges of pandering obscenity and using 
children in nudityrelated material 
some say the furor surrounding the trial and the traveling 
exhibit has helped the art world by drawing record crowds to 
galleries and forcing artists to become politically active to 
support their work 
it has brought a lot of artists out of their studios to 
organize and demonstrate their own moral and political strength for 
the first time since the end of the vietnam war said david ross 
director of the institute of contemporary art in boston where the 
photos were exhibited 
i think the silver lining has been that the art world has been 
given a sense of direction that it didnt have before 
the exhibit combined mapplethorpes explicit homoerotic 
photographs the source of the controversy with cool elegant 
portraits and photographs of flowers mapplethorpe helped organize 
the show shortly before he died of aids in march 1989 at age 42 
boston was the last stop on the exhibits sevencity tour about 
103000 people saw the show during its nine weeks at the institute 
about twice the number that visited the museum all last year said 
arthur cohen director of marketing membership in the museum also 
has surged recently he added 
but cohen said the increased income from the show was offset by 
higher security and insurance costs the net income came to less 
than half the amount lost in grants recently 
were not even coming out even he said 
in washington dc 48000 people saw the show during its 
threeweek stay at the washington project for the arts a popular 
10week exhibit there usually draws 8000 said philip brookman 
who curated that show after it was canceled at the corcoran gallery 
of art 17 months ago 
our membership has increased quite a bit our attendance has 
been consistently high since the mapplethorpe show brookman 
said it was received very positively by critics and the public 
at large mothers came in with their children 
others saw the shows aftermath differently 
were worse off for mapplethorpe in the long run were much 
worse off said rita burke president of morality in media of 
massachusetts 
burke said the lesson for her in the mapplethorpe show was that 
the normal person is helpless to fight the media 
i think it has raised consciousness to how difficult it is for 
the average person who is really turned off by material like 
this she said i find that an awful lot of people are giving 
up they wring their hands 
the exhibit attracted little attention in its first showings in 
philadelphia and chicago but in washington it caught the eye of 
sen jesse helms rnc 
helms and other congressional conservatives were angered by 
several photographs with homosexual and sadomasochistic subjects 
their attack forced the corcoran to cancel the show in mid1989 
since then the focus has shifted to two photographs of two 
children with exposed genitals 
morality in media was unsuccessful in attempts to bring criminal 
charges against the boston institute 
