<TEXT>
while the brunt of a government shutdown 
saturday would not hit for three days visitors to the statue of 
liberty the washington monument and yellowstone national park 
would feel the effects at once 
white house budget director richard darman told agency heads 
they should be ready to send home all nonessential employees 
scheduled to work saturday his memo cited the failure by congress 
to pass legislation to fund the government byond a midnight friday 
deadline 
the bulk of the federal work force of 24 million was told to 
report to work tuesday even if only to be sent home after a few 
hours monday is a federal holiday 
barring a lastminute compromise this would be the fourth time 
over the past decade that the federal government has sent its 
employees home because its authority to spend money expired the 
last time in 1986 the impasse lasted half a day 
then the statue of liberty the washington monument and st 
louis gateway arch all were closed because park service workers 
were sent home 
this time tourists to the nations captial would find the 
smithsonian institutions 12 museums closed too white house 
gardeners hung up their rakes and left 
the park service prepared to shut down these monuments saturday 
and to padlock everything that can be padlocked said bob 
walker a spokesman for the interior department 
if a visitor wants to drive into yellowstone or shenandoah 
park therell be no one there to keep them out or charge them a 
toll to get in but those people would be largely on their own 
walker said if their car broke down there would be no friendly 
ranger to help them 
the postal service would not be affected by the shutdown because 
it is not dependent on government appropriations 
amtrak rail passenger service would not be immediately affected 
for the same reason it does however receive a large government 
subsidy so that its operations would be hard hit if the budget 
impasse is long lasting 
president bush convened an emergency cabinet meeting to discuss 
details of a government shutdown 
his spokesman marlin fitzwater said there would be significant 
disruptions of government services beginning on saturday and each 
day they would grow a little worse 
each agency decides what is an essential service but 
generally employees whose jobs are needed for protecting public 
health or safety such as air traffic controllers prison guards 
and the military would be allowed to keep working 
beginning saturday morning the head of each agency must be 
prepared to implement his or her existing plan for closing down 
operations darman said in a memo to the agency heads 
only those services needed to protect life and property will 
be permitted to continue in the absence of a budget agreement 
darman said 
a spokesman for the federal aviation administration bob 
buckhorn said that if we have a shutdown essential services 
remain in place including air traffic controllers other faa 
employes who deal with safety would also continue working he said 
every office in the commerce department except the national 
weather service would be affected by a shutdown a commerce 
spokesman said 
the shutdown would hit nasa at an awkward time shortly before 
midnight fueling is to begin for an early morning launch of the 
space shuttle discovery 
no one is suggesting a layoff for the five astronauts who 
during the fourday mission are scheduled to deploy the ulysses 
probe on its fiveyear journey to the sun 
however the government technically will lack the authority to 
pay employees for their work because none of the 13 appropriations 
bills needed to fund the government for the fiscal year that began 
monday has been enacted 
after the government was forced to shut down briefly in 1981 
1984 and 1986 congress voted to reimburse all federal employees 
for lost pay 
this time the situation was complicated by the fact that the 
governments power to borrow money was also expiring at midnight 
friday unless congress passed and bush signed an extension of the 
federal debt limit 
at the agriculture department workers who normally work on 
weekends primarily forest service workers were told they would 
likely be sent home saturday 
kelly ship a department spokeswoman said only that a handful 
of the departments 100000 employees nationwide would be 
considered essential and expected to report to work during a 
shutdown she added 
state and county offices of major usda agencies such as the 
farmers home administration and the agricultural stabilization and 
conservation service would close 
federal meat and poultry inspection however would continue 
during a general shutdown she said 
a pentagon spokesman said senior department officials were in 
closed meetings friday afternoon discussing what actions would be 
required on saturday if the government were shut down 
the spokesman jim turner said the department would not comment 
on its contingency plans 
the pentagon has more than 3 million employees including 21 
million uniformed personnel it appeared unlikely that any forced 
shutdown of defense department operations would affect the 
deployment of more than 170000 servicemen and women in the persian 
gulf 
at the state department officials said that all personnel are 
expected to show up tuesday but that nonessential employees would 
be sent home no estimate was available on the number of employees 
in that category 
