economy increase already artificially high costs to consumers of 
several basic goos and abrogate our international agreements 
bush said in a veto message 
disputing claims by the bills supporters bush said the textile 
industry was doing well domestic production has been up slightly 
since 1987 he said and unemployment in major textileproducing 
states is lower than the national average 
economic indicators illustrate that the problems this bill is 
intended to address do not exist bush said 
the consumer costs of all restrictions on textile and apparel 
imports are conservatively estimated to increase to a total of 160 
billion over the next five years bush said that amounts to an 
onerous 2600 for a family of four over that same period 
these costs would continue to rise annually he added in 
