presiding episcopal bishop edmond l browning said an atmosphere 
of tensions apparent diplomatic stalemate and threat of war 
had moved him to speak out on the situation 
in a statement addressed to the churchs bishops and its 25 
million members including bush browning called for cooperative 
and peaceful solutions 
in spite of the near unanimity of the united nations in 
confronting the crisis the time is fraught with danger he said 
huge armies and armadas led by those of our own country face 
each other with the promise of unimaginable destruction and 
havoc 
although supporting the un sanctions against iraqs naked 
aggression and saying iraq must withdraw completely from iraq 
browning questioned some western motives 
for what reason has our nation unleashed the greatest military 
force since the vietnam war he said are we not justified in 
suspecting that the reason is primarily economic having to do with 
unimpeded access to oil 
he urged examination of our national priorites and our 
addiction to unnecessary consumption 
he said he prayed that bush adhere to un resolutions and i 
pray for him as he wrestles with the difficult decisions of his 
office i urge that he remain steadfast and never give in to the 
trap of war 
declaring this is not a time for propaganda but for sober 
truth browning cautioned that we not demonize stereotype or 
oversimplify in assessments of the iraqi people 
resist the misplaced national pride which refuses to recognize 
the face of christ in your brother and sister in iraq and the 
middle east 
browning said the crisis is interconnected with the palestinian 
problem and must be seen in that light rather than as an isolated 
incident 
he said i continue to believe firmly that the united nations 
and the arab states themselves working in concert offer the best 
hope for a bloodless solution to the conflict 
