<TEXT>
this financially troubled city sued 
a judge who gave away city hall to pay a debt but the new owners 
lawyer says the propertys already been sold 
the suit filed friday in federal court seeks to reverse the 
sept 27 county circuit court ruling awarding city hall and some 
other city land to the guardians of a man who won a 34 million 
judgment after being injured in the city jail 
mayor carl officer contends in the 125 million lawsuit that the 
ruling by st clair county circuit judge roger scrivner was part of 
a pattern of racism against the predominantly black city the mayor 
also called for a us senate investigation of the circuit court 
the mayors suit filed in us district court on behalf of the 
people of east st louis alleged the circuit court has engaged 
in a pattern and practice of racially motivated conduct that has 
deprived the city of east st louis and its citizens of due process 
of law 
the mayor also asked the circuit court to reconsider scrivners 
decision and bar him from handling other cases involving the city 
said city attorney eric vickers 
scrivner awarded city hall and a piece of cityowned industrial 
property to walter debow 55 who suffered permanent brain damage 
after being beaten into a coma by a fellow prisoner at the city 
jail more than six years ago debow has no shortterm memory and is 
being cared for at a headinjury rehabilitation center in new 
jersey 
calls for comment to scrivner and the chief judge of the court 
werent returned friday 
debows attorney clyde kuehn said friday hed already made a 
deal to sell city hall he refused to name the prospective buyer or 
give the price 
kuehn said scrivners ruling was the only way to get the city to 
pay its debt to debow about 4 million because of interest 
the rights that were enforced in circuit court were the rights 
of a black man and a good guy too said attorney clyde kuehn 
referring to the allegation of racism you can win a 4 million 
verdict but you dont win until they pay 
debow who was in jail on charges of illegally transporting 
alcohol when the beating occurred needs the money to pay for his 
325perday care his family said 
the citys lawsuit seeks 25 million in actual damages and 100 
million in punitive damages 
the st clair county recorder of deeds said friday the property 
was placed in a trust oct 1 with eric rhein as guardian a phone 
call to rheins belleville law office was not immediately returned 
city hall is worth about 10 million vickers has said and city 
officials had been negotiating with a company to buy the other 
piece of property for 5 million to build a trash recycling plant 
east st louis is plagued by debt estimated at 47 million gov 
james r thompson signed a 34 million bailout bill aug 30 the 
money will come from state bond issues 
the population of the city which has one of the nations 
highest murder rates fell from 55000 in 1980 to 40000 this year 
the census bureau estimates 
selling the property rids debow of responsibility for paying 
property taxes which could be as high as 400000 annually on city 
hall alone kuehn said thursday 
it also eliminates potential liability for injuries on the 
property he said 
</TEXT>
