<TEXT>
american dream an emotional uncompromising 
documentary of the hormel meatpackers strike in the mid1980s is 
very much hot off the presses 
it was completed the day before its screening thursday at the 
new york film festival and the director hopes the success of 
roger and me means theres an audience for her film too 
but it will be a tough sell for barbara kopple whose 1976 
movie harlan county usa won an academy award for best 
feature documentary american dream tells a bleak story with 
little of the irony and dark humor that made roger and me so 
entertaining despite its account of corporate greed and 
indifference in flint mich 
speaking at a press conference at the festival where the movie 
received an extended ovation kopple spoke of the years she spent 
in austin minn the location of the strike and her desire to 
gain national attention for the documentary 
i think roger and me is a film that takes a different look 
at the problems of working people and i enjoyed it very much 
said kopple whose other films include no nukes and civil 
rights the struggle continues 
i just want to follow in its footsteps she said 
the film begins in 1984 with geo a hormel amp co asking workers 
to accept wage cuts although the company was turning a profit 
hormel which said it needed the reductions to remain competitive 
had enjoyed good relations with workers over the years and several 
plants agreed to the concessions 
but austins local p9 of the united food and commercial workers 
decided to fight ray rogers a maverick consultant known for 
organizing jp stevens textile mills in the south was recruited 
and the union followed his policy of confrontation 
hormel would not back down and on aug 17 1985 the nearly 
1500 members of local p9 walked off their jobs the national 
union urged rogers and p9 president jim guyette to negotiate but 
they angrily refused and most of the workers supported them 
the strike dragged on for months and became increasingly bitter 
workers lashed out at hormel and fought with each other as the 
company filled their jobs with replacement workers some employees 
their strike fund cut off by the national union crossed the picket 
lines 
hormel eventually returned the plant to full capacity and most 
of the strikers never returned to work some remain in austin 
others looked for jobs elsewhere 
kopple had access to local and national union officials she 
shows meatpackers breaking down and crying and lifelong friendships 
being destroyed there is a brief moment of humor a closeup of a 
billboard reading enjoy austin where the good life is here to 
stay 
there was a lot of media there for the strike koppel said 
but im not a newsperson i have a much more personal style i 
wanted to get inside peoples heads im very sympathetic to 
peoples making decent wages and wanted to make an explanation of 
what happened 
</TEXT>
