<TEXT>
a sculpture of st george slaying a dragon 
made from the wreckage of american and soviet nuclear missiles was 
dedicated friday on the grounds of the united nations 
the nuclear dragon is the ultimate evil said soviet foreign 
minister eduard shevardnadze at a ceremony attended by us 
secretary of state james baker iii un secretary general javier 
perez de cuellar and the artist zurab tsereteli 
here are these monsters born not of the artists imagination 
but of the cruel realities of our time the pershing and ss20 
nuclear missiles shevardnadze added they have been beheaded 
and destroyed not by the artists fantasy but by the will of the 
governments and people of those countries where they once came into 
being 
the 39foothigh monument depicts in bronze st george atop a 
rearing horse holding a long pole topped by a tiny cross the 
rider spears broken ss20 and pershing missiles the missiles form 
the body of a twoheaded dragon 
entitled good defeats evil it weighs 40 tons 
pershing and ss20 missiles were dismantled under the 
intermediate range nuclear forces treaty which was signed dec 8 
1987 by president reagan and soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
shevardnadze said his country was giving the sculpture to the 
united nations in honor of its 45th anniversary which is 
celebrated this month 
tsereteli told several hundred people who gathered at the 
sculpture dedication that he got the idea for the monument in a 
dream in which st george was slaying dragons made from missiles 
after the inf treaty was signed tsereteli got hold of some 
actual missile parts and gave them to an international group of 
children who were attending an art workshop with soviet children in 
his native georgia 
the children destroyed these missiles he said explaining 
that observing the children helped inspire him 
tsereteli 56 is the soviet unions artist laureate and has 
been named peoples artist of the ussr in 1976 he was awarded 
the lenin prize which honors contributions to culture 
with his 12yearold grandson vaseli tsereteli the artist 
placed a bright yellow bow with long streamers on the green 
sculpture tsereteli said this symbolized his hope for peace in the 
middle east and fulfilled the dream in which he visualized the 
sculpture as green and yellow 
</TEXT>
