<TEXT>
a new analysis of the sexual behavior of 
dozens of men infected with the aids virus has implicated oral sex 
between men as a greater risk than many scientists had assumed 
the researchers looked at 82 men at three continuing san 
francisco bay area studies who tested positive for hiv the virus 
that causes aids of the 82 17 percent reported they engaged in 
oral sex and no other behavior that carries a high risk of catching 
aids 
oral sex was not implicated as a major risk factor in previous 
studies one of the primary researchers warren winkelstein said 
friday what this study does is show pretty clearly that it is a 
strong risk factor 
weve always pointed out that oral sex was a potential risk 
now weve confirmed it added winkelstein professor of 
epidemiology at the university of california at berkeleys school 
of public health 
kent taylor spokesman for the federal centers for disease 
control said the findings were important 
were looking for more information on the transmission by way 
of oral sex because not a lot has been documented in this area 
taylor said i would say this is a very interesting finding this 
is obviously a very difficult topic to research 
epidemiologist michael samuel who presented the analysis this 
week at the american public health association annual meeting in 
new york city said the men analyzed became infected between 1984 
and 1990 
more than half of the 82 men engaged in receptive and insertive 
anal intercourse and receptive and insertive oral sex according to 
the study 
thirtyfour percent didnt engage in anal receptive intercourse 
which is known to carry a high risk of aids transmission but 
did participate in at least one of the other three behaviors and 
17 percent of the infected men reported only oral intercourse 
either receptive or insertive 
samuel said that the infection risk also was elevated with the 
use of a douche or enema before anal intercourse countering a 
belief by some that such actions might decrease a chance of hiv 
infection 
the data also confirmed findings of others studies that the 
risk was unmistakably higher for those with two to four partners 
than for those with one partner 
the new findings do not address the risks of oral sex between 
men and women they also do not indicate how the aids virus was 
transmitted during the oral sex or to what extent condoms or any 
other protective measures could have prevented infection 
on oct 1 1989 the san francisco health department reported 
the first two documented cases in which men became infected with 
the aids virus through oral sex 
former surgeon general c everett kopp had warned four years 
before that oral sex might be a transmission path for the aids 
virus but at the time health authorities and parts of the gay 
community were debating the issue 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
as of august 146746 have been diagnosed with aids in the united 
states since reporting began in 1981 as of aug 31 89761 deaths 
had been recorded 
</TEXT>
