<TEXT>
john schlesinger lately has been thinking a lot 
about alfred hitchcock 
actually he hasnt had much choice schlesingers latest film 
pacific heights is a psychological thriller with irresistible 
connections to the master of suspense himself questions are bound 
to arise 
based on a true story pacific heights stars melanie 
griffith and matthew modine as a young couple who purchase a large 
victorian house in san francisco and plan to rent rooms on the 
ground floor 
but they are nearly ruined when smoothtalking carter hayes 
michael keaton occupies one apartment and refuses to pay 
manipulating the legal system so griffith and modine end up on the 
wrong side of the law 
hitchcock would have loved it he specialized in making a little 
mayhem with ordinary lives turning an advertising executive 
into a fugitive in north by northwest and placing a dead body 
in a small new england town in the trouble with harry 
theres more schlesinger gave a minor role to tippi hedren 
griffiths mother and the star of two hitchcock films the 
birds and marnie he also makes a most hitchcocklike cameo 
schlesingers the heavyset man with a white beard riding the 
elevator with griffith in hitchcocks spellbound the 
director is seen leaving an elevator at the same time as gregory 
peck 
your defense mr schlesinger 
i havent made a study of his films in order to ape him 
said the director who has made some pretty fair movies himself 
including darling sunday bloody sunday and the academy 
awardwinning midnight cowboy 
but what hitchcock used to do quite often was take normal 
life yuppie life and from normalcy have something gradually creep 
up on you and as a child i saw the lady vanishes that wonderful 
film with dame may whitty and was haunted by the image of a 
bandaged head 
as far as the appearance i used to appear in all my films 
and then i said this is ridiculous hitchcock did this all the 
time so i stopped 
schlesinger fans will spot some of the directors own touches in 
pacific heights a sense of understatement an insistence that 
all ends remain loose and an everobservant camera that cases a 
room item by item like an electronic house detective 
i like the idea of using a camera to tell the story about 
people he said my doctor in london you can barely go sit in 
his consulting room because its filled with frogs little funny 
things hanging from the ceiling theres a scene in a lawyers 
office i thought why not make the lawyer collect frogs and 
introduce her with that image 
schlesinger born in london in 1926 was a character actor for 
stage film and televison and also made documentaries terminus 
won the golden lion for best documentary at the 1961 venice film 
festival 
the following year he established himself as one of englands 
finest young directors with a kind of loving and then made 
billy liar and darling for which julie christie won an 
academy award for best actress in 1965 he also managed to top 
hitchcock who never won an oscar by receiving one in 1969 for 
midnight cowboy 
his theory of directing life is doubleedged and movies should 
be too no schlesinger film ends with a couple walking 
handinhand into the sunset if it did hed probably make them 
escaped convicts or a guy with flowers arriving on top of a car 
as in a certain popular romantic comedy 
when i first heard about pretty woman i said ugh but 
its a very wellconfected film i had a good time 
if ive ever had any commercial success its been a total 
fluke i wouldnt have known midnight cowboy would have done so 
well 
schlesinger doesnt condemn pretty woman because hes also 
been guilty of relegating reality to a supporting role in 
marathon man a 1976 thriller with laurence olivier and dustin 
hoffman a vicious nazi olivier risks going to the jewish quarter 
in new york in search of diamonds 
great action schlesinger notes but unnecessary he didnt 
have to go to the jewish quarter to find about the diamonds 
and in the middle of pacific heights modine overhears 
keaton discussing his con game and has the incriminating evidence 
hes been hoping for but modine doesnt act on it and fails to 
tell police or his lawyer 
it would have ended the film laughed schlesinger who in 
his defense again summoned the spirit of poor mr hitchcock 
theres an expression applied to hitchcocks films called 
icebox logic icebox logic is as long as the film plays for the 
audience as theyre seeing it it doesnt matter if they go home 
and later when they open the fridge to get out the milk say to 
themselves now wait a moment why did they do this 
