muzi is a zulu in alien 
territory a migrant in a settled township and needs no time to 
think when asked what he hates most about living in a workers 
hostel 
everything is bad he said theres no privacy even in 
the toilets nothings being done 
he sat on one of four beds in a dark concreteblock room beneath 
a roof of corrugated metal a stocky bearded man with his arms 
wrapped across his chest grease and dirt stained the floor and 
walls a lone electric wire stretched overhead 
staying here you end up drinking muzi said im so tired 
of waiting 
the squalid hostels long a source of many social ills have 
become flash points of political violence that has killed nearly 
800 blacks in townships around johannesburg since aug 12 
many of the vicious street clashes have pitted hostel dwellers 
usually zulus like muzi against township residents from other 
tribes 
most of the zulus support the conservative inkatha movement 
based in their homeland in natal province and many township 
residents support the african national congress 
even south africas white government architect of the apartheid 
system that spawned the hostels has called for change president 
fw de klerk visited a soweto hostel in september and standing in 
a urinestained hall said the conditions were unacceptable 
officials have suggested converting some hostels to family 
dwellings but no action has been taken 
more than 130 hostels housing nearly 200000 people dot the 31 
black townships around johannesburg 
muzi who is 32 and has two children is one of countless blacks 
who for decades have left their families in impoverished rural 
areas to seek work in johannesburg the financial hub of south 
africa he would not reveal his last name 
apartheid laws made the move difficult requiring a migrant to 
obtain a job first in order to live in an urban township most 
restrictions were repealed in the 1980s but overcrowding in the 
townships has left migrant workers little choice but to live in the 
cramped singlesex dormitories without heat or indoor plumbing 
miserable living conditions combined with tribal and political 
rivalries encourage fighting 
the evil migrant labor system lies at the root of the 
current conflict said a group of national church leaders 
including desmond tutu the black anglican archbishop who won the 
1984 nobel peace prize 
other observers say its more complicated 
john kaneberman head of the respected institute of race 
relations a private organization said personal disputes 
political and tribal differences human nature and poor living 
conditions contribute to the violence 
its a lot of different factors and one might not be aware of 
them he said 
for example rooms in many hostels are segregated by tribe if a 
man has a fight with someone from another room and his friends get 
involved he said a personal dispute has the appearance of tribal 
fighting 
he insisted that tribal differences play a role despite 
statements to the contrary by black leaders 
its not fashionable in liberal circles to talk about black 
ethnic rivalry because the government used that argument as part of 
its divisive strategy he said 
kaneberman said township residents look down on the poorly 
educated rural workers creating class differences and the 
frustration and danger of hostel life compound the problems 
more than 5000 people live in some hostels like jabulani and 
merafe in soweto residents pay monthly rent of about 6 for a bed 
in a room that usually is shared by with at least three others 
many turn to prostitutes alcohol and drugs while away from 
their families 
the compounds are a social disaster not only in terms of 
separating breadwinners from families but in terms of the 
psychological strains placed on the workers in them jerry 
majatladi spokesman for the national union of mineworkers told 
the star newspaper 
