<TEXT>
new england telephone and new york telephone 
will make a voluntary 14 million payment to the us treasury and 
cut their longdistance rates 355 million to resolve allegations 
that they overcharged customers from 1984 to 1988 
the 14 million payment announced thursday as part of a 
consent decree between the companies and the federal communications 
commission is a record amount and is identical to a proposed fine 
the fcc had announced in february 
but the fcc said the payment was not a fine and it was making no 
finding of wrongdoing the commission said it was ending its 
enforcement action against the companies 
the 355 million is the interstate portion of an alleged 1185 
million in overcharges for equipment supplies and services the fcc 
had said the two phone companies paid materiel enterprises co the 
unregulated purchasing arm of new yorkbased nynex corp from 1984 
to 1988 nynex is the parent firm of new york and new england 
telephone 
the fcc had said the 355 million was charged to longdistance 
companies such as american telephone amp telegraph co mci and us 
sprint for connecting with the local phone network the 
longdistance companies pass those charges on to residential and 
business customers 
toby webb nynex vice president for government affairs said he 
could not estimate how much longdistance phone bills would be 
affected by the 355 million rebate 
local phone rates will not be affected 
nynex agreed to the 355 million rebate to be made within 30 
days and also said the two phone companies would reduce their 
capital accounts by 326 million to remove the alleged excess 
profits on plant and equipment purchased from meco materiel 
enterprises 
we hope this puts to rest any questions concerning nynexs 
desire to comply with all fcc regulations and policies in 
transactions among affiliate companies nynex chairman william c 
ferguson said in a statement 
