<TEXT>
the governments rail inspection system isnt 
good enough to guarantee that trains are running safely the 
general accounting office said today 
last year the government failed to inspect 1164 miles of 
track skipping over 18 percent of all railroads that own track 
the federal railroad administration also did not verify the 
accuracy of 54 percent of the accident or incident reports filed by 
railroads said the gao the investigative arm of congress 
fra does not have assurance that the nations 580 railroads 
are running safely gao associate director john w hill jr said 
in testimony submitted for a hearing today by the house energy and 
commerce subcommittee on transportation tourism and hazardous 
materials 
we found that 32 railroads did not receive any type of 
inspection in 1989 typically these were the smaller shortline 
railroads which have higher accident and injury rates than overall 
industry averages hill said 
because there are no standards telling railroad inspectors how 
often they must examine tracks signals equipment and operating 
practices there is no way to know whether the lack of annual 
inspections translates into a special safety risk he said 
the gao also criticized the fra for failing to pay special 
attention to railroads with poor safety histories or a string of 
accidents 
while the number of union pacific accidents in idaho more than 
doubled between 1986 and 1988 the total number of union pacific 
inspections in idaho decreased nearly 38 percent during this time 
period hill said 
