<TEXT>
a cut in shortterm interest rates by the 
federal reserve board could take months to affect the economy and 
even then it might be too little too late economists say 
some say that regardless of what type of federal budget 
agreement ultimately is approved they expect the central bank to 
moderately lower its target for the federal funds rate the 
interest banks charge each other for overnight loans to 7 percent 
from 8 percent 
but as the economy moves closer to recession it moves further 
from the feds control analysts say 
the fed is going to be pretty much impotent to stop whats 
already on track said ray stone of stone amp mccarthy research 
associates inc referring to beliefs that the economy is already 
in a recession or quickly headed for one 
such a small cut in the fed funds rate may be absorbed by banks 
trying to bolster earnings and never affect consumer and business 
loans through a cut in the prime rate said john lonski chief 
economist at moodys investors service inc a debtrating agency 
a lower fed funds rate would mean banks would pay a smaller 
wholesale price for money banks could widen their profit margin by 
holding the prime rate steady 
twenty five basis points onefourth of a percentage point 
for the most part will help shore up bank earnings whether or not 
well see any discernible difference in lending rates remains to be 
seen lonski said 
lonski and others anticipate another 25 basis point cut in the 
fed funds rate before long that would likely be enough to affect 
the prime he said 
it might be a longshot but a move to lower interest rates could 
have a psychological impact on consumers by making them more 
confident that the economy will recover soon 
consumer confidence has sagged and as people feel less secure 
in their jobs they are more prone to spend less money a signal 
that the fed is trying to move the economy could boost spending 
maybe theyll go out and buy that new car stone said 
others were more skeptical 
as far as consumer attitudes are concerned more people will be 
looking to the persian gulf than the federal reserve said alan 
levenson of the wefa group an economic forecasting firm in 
suburban philadelphia 
moreover its doubtful most consumers know or care what the fed 
funds rate is doing 
what the man on the street wants to see is a reduction in the 
cost in borrowing from banks such as a significant downward 
movement in variable rate mortgages lonski said 
economists warn that although fed chairman alan greenspan is 
confident that congressional approval of a credible budget 
agreement would lead to lower shortterm interest rates plans to 
ease monetary policy could still be scuttled 
members of the house fearful of taking tax hikes and spending 
cuts to their constituents less than a month before an election 
stalled passage of a compromise package of tax increases and 
spending cuts 
the house on friday rejected the 500 billion deficitreduction 
proposal backed by president bush and greenspan an alternative 
proposal might not be to greenspans liking and could steer the fed 
away from following a more generous credit course 
then theres inflation 
the persian gulf crisis has been sending oil prices on a 
rollercoaster ride fanning inflation fears 
more proof of the negative impact the middle east situation is 
having on us inflation will be available in a few weeks the 
labor department will release the september consumer price index on 
oct 18 it is expected to show a 1 percent jump 
many analysts have noted the fed appears more concerned with 
controlling inflation by keeping interest rates high than with 
spurring economic activity by cutting borrowing rates 
the rise in oil prices the budget impasse and the weaker 
dollar which increases the price of imports have been blamed for 
inhibiting the fed 
even assuming that congress eventually cracks the budget 
deadlock economists still warn that a sharp rise in prices could 
spook the fed from relaxing its guard against inflation 
