<DOCNO> AP901005-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the british pound will enter europes exchange 
rate mechanism a move that will link the currency closely to its 
european neighbors and limit exchange rate movements an official 
said today 
chancellor of the exchequer john major said that as part of the 
move which will take effect monday a key british interest rate 
will simultaneously drop by one percentage point to 14 percent 
joining the exchange rate mechanism symbolizes britains 
willingness to participate in european integration ahead of 1992 
when europe is scheduled to meld into one marketplace of 220 
million consumers 
despite the cooperative stance prime minister margaret thatcher 
still remains opposed to creating single a european central bank 
and a single currency 
the pound which had been rising in anticipation of the 
announcement surged on the news to 19360 from 19185 in early 
trading against the german mark the pound also catapulted to 
29953 marks from 29492 marks stock prices also soared 
the european communitys monetary committee is likely to approve 
the british plan for the pound to join the european monetary 
systems erm 
under the terms of entry national central banks are obliged to 
prevent their currencies from falling outside prescribed bands by 
direct market intervention 
the move which takes a freefloating pound and ties it to other 
currencies should limit disruptive exchange rate movements and 
promote economic stability 
a high pound also should help fight inflation by lowering the 
cost of imports 
thatcher agreed in principle to link the pound to the other 
currencies at a community summit meeting in madrid last year but 
said she would move only when britains inflation rate was lower 
however the government went ahead despite the current high 
inflation rate of 106 percent 
the pound will enter the mechanism at a central rate of 29500 
german marks and like the spanish peseta will be allowed to 
fluctuate by 6 percent above or below that rate the treasury said 
the other participating currencies are limited to a narrow 225 
percent band 
rates have been adjusted 12 times since the mechanisms 
inception 11 years ago the mechanism has avoided any major 
adjustments to rates in the last 3 12 years 
the other currencies already in the mechanism are the german 
mark the french franc the dutch guilder the italian lira the 
belgian and luxembourg francs the danish krone and the irish 
pound 
not participating are the portuguese escudo and the greek 
drachma 
</TEXT>
