<TEXT>
in the midst of a bear market on wall street 
some analysts are keeping busy searching out the seeds of future 
opportunities 
prolonged declines in stock prices are naturally painful and 
dispiriting to investors these observers acknowledge but they add 
that many of the best opportunities to buy stocks for handsome 
returns have come in periods of financial travail 
there is no question that the market is currently weak says 
george putnam iii in the current issue of his investment advisory 
publication the turnaround letter 
the word we hear most often to describe market conditions 
these days is ugly investors are very skittish and any bad news 
will send a stock plummeting 
but we view the current market as an attractive buying 
opportunity good companies in all categories have been hammered 
over the last two months and they will recover sharply when 
investors regain some confidence in the market 
it may not happen this month or even this year but it will 
happen 
or as barton biggs at the investment banking firm of morgan 
stanley amp co puts it the bear is aging in the us i think we 
are somewhere in the second half of a cyclical bear market in 
which the averages normally decline in the range of 20 percent to 
30 percent 
the bad news is no secret anymore everyone knows most of the 
bear story 
the news doesnt have to become good for stocks to stop going 
down just that it is less bad than what has already been 
discounted in prices 
the scare scenarios always seem more credible when the markets 
are falling but you have to be careful not to get more bearish as 
prices decline instead you logically should become more bullish 
because you can buy quality goods cheaper 
i think we have further to go in this bear market but as 
prices go down i want to begin averaging in 
observers like putnam and biggs readily concede how difficult it 
is to call a market bottom 
indeed some analysts contend that stocks are likely to keep 
sliding as long as it takes to discourage just about all the 
bargain hunters and selfproclaimed patient optimists 
this global bear market should still be respected and treated 
with great caution says stan weinstein publisher of the 
professional tape reader advisory in hollywood fla 
in the past week the market made some fitful efforts to rally 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials closed friday at 251064 
up 5816 from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index gained 285 to 
17070 the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market 
rose 1285 to 34736 and the american stock exchange market value 
index lost 124 to 30648 
volume on the big board averaged 16496 million shares a day 
against 17148 million the week before 
most analysts believe stock prices at recent levels have already 
taken into account a moderate relatively short recession their 
main worry is that confidence among investors will suffer some 
further blows raising the prospect of a deeper and longer slump 
in every bear phase there has been what seemed to be a 
plausible doomsday scenario that terrorized investors biggs 
said in retrospect most of them seem farfetched but they sure 
scared me at the time 
if the economic apocalypse does really come this time it 
wont happen overnight and my guess is that the central banks will 
try to inflate their way out 
we are not going through the end of the world just the end of 
the euphoria some gloomy rainy day for no clearly discernible 
reason stocks will stop declining 
</TEXT>
