<TEXT>
bond prices finished little changed friday after 
a volatile session in which failure to reach a federal budget 
accord overshadowed another rise in unemployment 
the treasurys benchmark 30year bond ended the day largely 
unchanged recovering from a sharp decline earlier in the day that 
pushed prices down about 6 per 1000 face amount the bonds 
yield dipped to 878 percent from 879 percent late thursday 
the house voted 254179 early friday to reject president bushs 
plan aimed at cutting 500 billion from the federal budget deficit 
bond traders said the rejection made it unlikely the federal 
reserve would take quick action to lower interest rates to spur the 
slumping economy which would boost the value of fixedincome 
instruments such as bonds 
the bond market for weeks has awaited a fed easing and pinned 
its hopes to the budget deal 
the market is realizing that without any federal budget 
accord the fed probably wont ease said kevin flanagan a money 
market economist with dean witter reynolds inc 
the budget collapse took precedence over the labor departments 
report that unemployment rose to 57 percent in september another 
sign of weakening but analysts said the report had some 
inflationary signals which dulled its impact on bonds 
the significance of the report was severely diminished because 
of the knowledge that the fed will not respond to any weak 
economic data until there is a budgetcutting accord said ward 
mccarthy of stone amp mccarthy research associates in princeton nj 
treasury bills dropped sharply at the markets opening with the 
discount yields on threemonth and oneyear bills dropping below 7 
percent for a short time for the first time since august 1988 all 
maturities began rebounding around midmorning 
economists attributed some of the gain to president bushs 
stance refusing to sign emergency legislation to keep the 
government operating that was seen as an attempt by the white 
house to press for a quick resolution to the budget impasse 
in the secondary market for treasury bonds prices of 
shortterm intermediate and longterm government issues all ranged 
from unchanged to up 116 point according to telerate inc a 
financial information service 
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of 10 in the 
price of a bond with a 1000 face value 
