<TEXT>
the travelers corp said friday it is 
adding 650 million to its reserves to cover expected real estate 
losses a move that will result in a thirdquarter net loss of 500 
million 
the hartfordbased insurance company will also reduce its 
quarterly dividend from 60 cents to 40 cents per share 
edward h budd travelers chairman and chief executive officer 
said reserves were boosted to cover expected losses in the 
companys mortgage loan and real estate investments 
he blamed the sharp decline in the commercial real estate 
market 
following an intensive review of our mortgage loans and real 
estate holdings we determined it appropriate to increase reserves 
to provide for real estate losses which we expect to emerge over a 
number of years budd said 
the company said this was the first major addition to reserves 
since june 1988 when travelers added 415 million to cover 
anticipated real estate losses the latest increase boosts reserves 
to 115 billion at quarters end 
travelers said it will post a net loss of 500 million in the 
quarter compared with net income of 94 million for the same 
period last year the company also will have a net loss for the 
year budd said 
he said the onethird reduction in the quarterly dividend to 
save 100 million by the end of 1991 will allow the company to 
retain more earnings to support growth 
despite its losses in the real estate market the company said 
its main businesses continue to be strong 
budd said the company has made progress in restructuring its 
insurance operations generating cost improvements of nearly 200 
million in the past two years he said the company wrote a record 
13 billion in new business in the managed care and employee 
benefits area in 1989 
the company expects operating profits in the third quarter to 
surpass 1989 levels of 63 million and operating income for 1990 
to rise by about 25 percent above last year 
