<TEXT>
a federal judge friday again extended a freeze 
on payments to asbestos disease victims by the manville trust fund 
pending completion of a courtordered reorganization 
us district judge jack b weinstein said the monthlong 
extension was needed to finalize an agreement on a restructuring in 
which manville corp would inject up to 520 million over seven 
years to reverse a cash shortfall 
the shortage has jeopardized compensation payments to tens of 
thousands of victims the agreement to refinance the trust was 
announced last month the payments by manville would begin late 
next year 
it was the third monthlong extension by weinstein on the 
payments freeze which applies to all claims or court judgments 
made since the first order in august or until the new nov 6 
expiration date 
the trust was created in 1988 as part of manvilles bankruptcy 
court reorganization which was forced by mounting liability for 
lung cancer and other serious and fatal diseases caused by 
asbestos 
under the freeze the trust is permitted to make payments for 
hardship claims and emergency health needs as well as operating 
expenses legal fees of trust attorneys and fees to a court adviser 
overseeing the restructuring 
the trust to date has settled close to 24000 claims for more 
than 1 billion from people made sick by inhaling asbestos fibers 
mostly during shipbuilding and other construction 
the trust faces 130000 more claims it cant meet weinstein 
ordered the reorganization after the trust said it was out of money 
to pay new claims it said would not be met until well into the 21st 
century 
the reorganization is designed to speed payments and alter the 
compensation scheme so that claims are processed based on victims 
health and financial need rather than when they file a claim 
</TEXT>
